{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3e0a095c-f6cb-4fee-b535-8e75322aeaee","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with your current SDK. This is what you need after an SDK update.\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the *same* versions already recorded; it fixes corrupted installations but doesn't fetch newer packages.\n\nSince the SDK moved forward and your workloads are stale, `update` will pull the matching MAUI workload bits for the new SDK. After running it, do a clean build:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet clean\ndotnet build\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1b54cfa5-ff57-48a2-a621-6a2a8eaf868c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search any codebase for this.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":232,"requestId":"E852:1EDE:224FDA:28B931:69F93E28"},"id":"fc0d3709-fd3a-4750-bfc1-c64ebd55d3a2","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:47:43.552Z","parentId":"b71ad3fc-9659-4866-8e1e-70e38ffba49d"}
